            "body": "Sorry, never mind, it's the other way round actually:\n\nLast year, *Vim* [had code removed](https://github.com/vim/vim/commit/e6d8b4662ddf9356da53f56e363b67b524fd8825#diff-3d4f1d41e96bee10ce91bae82327d0607f06b90b168223fee42eb08adb37bfe4L441-L445) that would normally override the default `Visual` colors in sufficiently color-capable terminals. It has been like this in Vim releases since 9.1.0061 (way newer than what Debian gives me of course). After some more follow-up changes, the default `Visual` colors [are now simply](https://github.com/vim/vim/blob/97baa1cfe83c08eff1a452aca8d91f51112ca932/src/highlight.c#L318):\n\n```c\n\t \"Visual ctermbg=Grey ctermfg=Black guibg=LightGrey guifg=Black\"),\n```\n\nThis exactly matches what you guys then put into the `vim` color scheme (and what is seen in my Neovim screenshot above): https://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/c7d13f2895fa657ff3d9d45741f9abec25072b56/runtime/colors/vim.lua#L243\n\nSo if anything I'd have to take it up with the guys at the original Vim. Neovim did everything right âœ… ",
